{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501790"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:34:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:34:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1791"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1791"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.7,0.12,0.04,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1791"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52075"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1791"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1791"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37392"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"390"},{"type":"tags","id":"1181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1432"},{"type":"tags","id":"2163"},{"type":"tags","id":"2798"},{"type":"tags","id":"2965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8222"},{"type":"tags","id":"8275"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6061"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7356"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14541"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42404"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45069"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52075"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a painless swelling in her neck. She is a recent migrant from Afghanistan. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a firm, non-tender 2.5 cm swelling in the lower aspect of the left anterior triangle of the neck that moves when the patient swallows.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal a TSH level of 4 mIU/L (0.5-5). Thyroid ultrasound shows a solid, hypoechoic nodule that is 2.3 cm in size with irregular margins. Cytological examination with fine needle aspiration (FNA) of the swelling shows enlarged irregular nuclei and necrotic cells with concentric calcification.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sarcoidosis","Papillary thyroid carcinoma","Follicular adenoma","Toxic adenoma","Thyroglossal duct cyst"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a thyroid nodule that has several concerning features for malignancy. The identification of rounded, calcified collections on cytological examination, known as psammoma bodies, is diagnostic of \u003Cstrong\u003Epapillary thyroid carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Additionally, the ultrasound findings of a solid, hypoechoic nodule larger than 2 cm with irregular margins are highly suspicious for malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with systemic symptoms such as fever, weight loss, and pulmonary symptoms. While it can involve peripheral lymph nodes, the presentation and cytology findings in this case are not consistent with sarcoidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollicular adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign thyroid neoplasm that cannot be distinguished from follicular carcinoma on FNA alone. The cytology findings in this case, particularly the presence of psammoma bodies, are not consistent with follicular adenoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxic adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a cause of hyperthyroidism, which would present with a suppressed TSH. In this case, the TSH is within the normal range. Additionally, the ultrasound and cytology findings are not consistent with a toxic adenoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroglossal duct cyst\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a midline neck mass that moves with swallowing and tongue protrusion. It is usually detected in childhood and would not have the cytological features described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of ultrasound findings (solid, hypoechoic nodule with irregular margins) and cytology results (enlarged irregular nuclei, necrotic cells, and psammoma bodies) strongly support the diagnosis of papillary thyroid carcinoma. This is the most common type of thyroid cancer, accounting for about 80% of all thyroid malignancies. Further management would typically involve referral to an endocrinologist or head and neck surgeon for consideration of total thyroidectomy, followed by radioactive iodine therapy if indicated based on staging.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Elevated TSH levels and a solid nodule with irregular margins on ultrasound are highly associated with thyroid cancer.","Psammoma bodies on cytology of a thyroid nodule are highly suggestive of papillary thyroid carcinoma."],"references":["Limaiem F, Rehman A, Mazzoni T. Papillary Thyroid Carcinoma. In: StatPearls [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK536943/","Te HS, Perlman DM, Shenoy C, et al. Clinical characteristics and organ system involvement in sarcoidosis: comparison of the University of Minnesota Cohort with other cohorts. BMC Pulm Med. 2020;20(1). Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7268634/","Kasper DL, Fauci AS, Hauser SL, Longo DL, Lameson JL, Loscalzo J. Harrison\u0027s Principles of Internal Medicine. New York, NY: McGraw-Hill Education; 2015","Foley DS, Fallat ME. Thyroglossal duct and other congenital midline cervical anomalies. Semin Pediatr Surg. 2006;15(2):70\u201375. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16616309/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37392"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1791"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37392"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-02T11:32:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-02T11:33:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1791"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52075"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"